SIMPLE: propitious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Propitious
<hw>Pro*pi"tious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>propitius</ets>, perhaps originally a term of augury meaning,
flying forward (<ets>pro</ets>) or well; cf. Skr. <ets>pat</ets> to fly,
E. <ets>petition</ets>, <ets>feather</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Convenient; auspicious; favorable; kind; <as>as, a
<ex>propitious</ex> season; a <ex>propitious</ex> breeze.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, kind; gracious; merciful; helpful; -- said of
a person or a divinity.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now t' assuage the force of this new flame,⟦br⟧
And make thee [Love] more <qex>propitious</qex> in my need.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Auspicious; favorable; kind.</syn> --
<usage><er>Propitious</er>, <er>Auspicious</er>. <xex>Auspicious</xex>
(from the ancient idea of <xex>auspices</xex>, or omens) denotes
⟦ldquo⟧indicative of success,⟦rdquo⟧ or ⟦ldquo⟧favored by incidental
occurrences;⟦rdquo⟧ as, an <xex>auspicious</xex> opening; an
<xex>auspicious</xex> event. <xex>Propitious</xex> denotes that which
efficaciously protect us in some undertaking, speeds our exertions, and
decides our success; as, <xex>propitious</xex> gales;
<xex>propitious</xex> influences.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pro*pi"tious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pro*pi"tious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proplasm</ent>⟦br⟧
